# ADR-0001: Core Technology Decisions

## Status

Accepted

## Context

**{{ display_name }}** is a new frontend project. Before writing any application code, the team evaluated the key technology choices that define how the project is built, tested, and maintained.

This ADR records the decisions made at project inception and their rationale so that future contributors understand why the project is structured the way it is.

### Key Requirements

- Fast initial page load and good Core Web Vitals
- Strong developer experience with type safety
- Clear conventions that an AI agent or new team member can follow
- Maintainable component architecture as the project grows
{% if use_auth %}
- Secure authentication with session management
{% endif %}
{% if use_i18n %}
- Support for multiple languages from the start
{% endif %}

---

## Decision 1: Next.js {{ nextjs_version }} with {{ router | replace("-", " ") | title }}

### Why Next.js {{ nextjs_version }}

{% if nextjs_version == "15" %}
Next.js 15 was chosen over alternatives (Remix, Vite + React Router, Astro) because:

- Stable App Router with React Server Components is production-ready
- Turbopack in `next dev` delivers fast HMR at scale
- Built-in image optimisation, font loading, and metadata APIs eliminate boilerplate
- Strong ecosystem - most third-party libraries have first-class Next.js support
- Vercel deployment target, but also deployable to any Node.js host or via Docker
{% else %}
Next.js 14 was chosen for its stable App Router and proven production track record while Next.js 15 stabilises in the ecosystem.
{% endif %}

### Why {{ router | replace("-", " ") | title }}

{% if router == "app-router" %}
The App Router was chosen over the Pages Router because:

- **React Server Components** allow data fetching in the component tree without client waterfalls
- **Nested layouts** are a first-class concept - no custom layout wrapping needed
- **Streaming** with Suspense delivers faster perceived performance
- **Route Groups** allow fine-grained layout scoping without URL changes
- The App Router is the future of Next.js - the Pages Router is in maintenance mode

**Trade-off:** The App Router has a steeper learning curve (Server vs Client component boundaries, caching behaviour). This is mitigated by `docs/architecture.md` and `AI_CONTEXT.md`.
{% else %}
The Pages Router was chosen because:

- The team is familiar with its data fetching model (`getServerSideProps`, `getStaticProps`)
- All third-party libraries are well-tested against the Pages Router
- The simpler mental model reduces onboarding time
- Migration to App Router can happen incrementally if needed

**Trade-off:** No React Server Components or nested layouts. Data fetching happens at the page level, not the component level.
{% endif %}

