## Decision 2: {{ language | title }}

{% if language == "typescript" %}
TypeScript strict mode was chosen because:

- Catch type errors at compile time, not in production
- Self-documenting component props and API contracts
- IDE support (autocomplete, refactoring) is significantly better
- Required for `shadcn/ui`, TanStack Query, and other key libraries

`tsconfig.json` uses `"strict": true`. Disable rules sparingly with `// @ts-expect-error` and a comment explaining why.
{% else %}
JavaScript was chosen to reduce initial friction. JSDoc annotations are used for type hints where it matters.

**Recommendation:** Plan a TypeScript migration. The project structure and component conventions are compatible with TypeScript adoption at any time.
{% endif %}

---

## Decision 3: {{ styling }} for Styling

{% if styling == "tailwind" %}
**Tailwind CSS** was chosen over CSS Modules, SCSS, and Styled Components because:

- Utility-first approach eliminates naming decisions for one-off styles
- Co-located styles with JSX reduce context switching
- Design token system via `tailwind.config.ts` ensures visual consistency
- `cva` (class-variance-authority) handles component variants cleanly
- Strong ecosystem: `shadcn/ui`, `tailwind-merge`, `tailwind-animate`

**Trade-off:** Long className strings can be hard to read. Mitigated by `cva` for variant components and `cn()` helper for conditional class merging.
{% elif styling == "css-modules" %}
**CSS Modules** was chosen for scoped, collocated styles with zero runtime overhead.

- No JavaScript-in-CSS runtime cost
- Standard CSS - no new syntax to learn
- Excellent IDE support for class name refactoring
- Compatible with any CSS features (custom properties, `@layer`, `@container`)

**Trade-off:** More file context switching than Tailwind; requires a naming convention for class names.
{% elif styling == "styled-components" %}
**Styled Components** was chosen for its component-first styling model and dynamic theming capabilities.

- Theme tokens are TypeScript-typed
- Dynamic styles based on props without extra CSS variables
- Co-located styles in component files

**Trade-off:** Runtime CSS-in-JS has a performance cost. Requires SSR configuration to avoid FOUC. Consider migrating to zero-runtime alternatives (Linaria, Panda CSS) if performance becomes critical.
{% elif styling == "scss" %}
**SCSS** was chosen for its familiar syntax and powerful features (nesting, mixins, functions).

- Compiles to standard CSS with no runtime overhead
- Partial system organises global tokens cleanly
- Module files (`.module.scss`) provide component-level scoping

**Trade-off:** Requires maintaining SCSS abstracts as the design system evolves. Nesting can lead to specificity problems if not disciplined.
{% endif %}

